<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate carpet in square yards?", answer: "Carpet is sold by the square yard. Multiply the room length by width in feet to get square feet, divide by 9 to convert to square yards, then add 10 percent for waste and cut-in. A 12 × 15 foot room is 180 sq ft or 20 sq yd, plus 2 sq yd waste — order 22 sq yd. Always round up." },
  { question: "How wide is a carpet roll?", answer: "The standard carpet roll width is 12 feet. Some manufacturers also make 15 foot rolls and less commonly 13'2\" (for Berber). If either dimension of your room exceeds the roll width, you will need a seam. Most rooms under 12 feet wide are seamless; larger rooms almost always have seams, which a good installer can make nearly invisible." },
  { question: "How much waste should I add for carpet?", answer: "10 percent is standard for a rectangular room with minimal cuts. Add 15 percent for rooms with multiple doorways, alcoves, or irregular shapes. Patterned carpet requires 15 to 20 percent because the installer must match the pattern across seams, which wastes more material. Stairs require 20 to 25 percent waste." },
  { question: "How much does carpet cost per square yard?", answer: "Builder-grade polyester and nylon run 15 to 25 dollars per square yard for the carpet itself, excluding pad and installation. Midrange nylon runs 25 to 45 dollars per sq yd. Wool and premium synthetic fiber runs 50 to 100+ dollars. Add 7 to 15 dollars per sq yd for padding plus 5 to 10 dollars per sq yd for installation. Total installed cost is usually 30 to 70 dollars per sq yd for most homeowners." },
  { question: "Will my room need a seam?", answer: "If the shorter dimension of the room is more than 12 feet, yes. The calculator flags this automatically. Good seams run perpendicular to the main light source (not into a door) and are placed in low-traffic areas. Professional installers use heat-activated seam tape and a seam iron to make seams nearly invisible, especially in plush and textured carpets." }
]) %>

